#Summary1=(human1) Comedy writers Wayne and Anne discuss the importance of collaboration, community and friendship in the writers' room for a show such as Jimmy Fallon's Late Night, continuing after flop jokes, and trying new ideas with collaborators despite the risk of looking like an idiot.

#Summary2=(claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022) The article discusses writers' room dynamics in TV comedy, featuring Wayne Federman, who became head monologue writer for Jimmy Fallon through an unconventional path, and Anne Lane, who took a traditional route and emphasizes the importance of improv skills and resilience in collaborative comedy writing.

#Summary3=(gpt4o) In this article, Ryan Merkley discusses Wayne Federman's unique journey to becoming head monologue writer for Jimmy Fallon, emphasizing the collaborative nature of writers' rooms and contrasting it with Anne Lane's traditional approach, which highlights the importance of improv and adaptation in comedy writing.

#Summary4=(Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct) Comedians Wayne Federman and Anne Lane share their experiences working in late-night TV writers' rooms, describing the creative process and how they developed ideas for Jimmy Fallon's show.

#Summary5=(Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct) Wayne's unconventional path to leading Jimmy Fallon's writers' room involved working closely with Fallon on tour before taking the role, while Anne followed a more traditional route through submitting writing samples, and both emphasized the importance of collaboration, improvisation, and maintaining a positive attitude towards feedback in a creative environment.
#Text=Wayne has written with comedy legend Judd Apatow , penned lines for major awards shows , and was the head monologue writer for Jimmy Fallon when Fallon was doing Late Night .

#Text=So I remember , like a couple of months into the Fallon job , which was one of the greatest jobs I 've had in my life , one of the greatest jobs you can have is running a monologue room for late night thing .
#Text=Even like three months in , I was like , oh , this feels like school .
#Text=It feels like you have to get up and go to school .
#Text=It was like a workday hours .
#Text=I do n't really love getting up in the morning .
#Text=Anne and Wayne both told me that while an episode of TV is usually credited to 1 or 2 writers , everything always starts with a group of smart , funny people sitting around a table .
#Text=One year I had like my own little off- , like a little just office , like very -- as small as you could .
#Text=And then when we moved to a different location , it was -- I was part of like the production team , like the person that was doing the bookings was three desks away .
#Text=So it was all very chaotic and there was no privacy .
#Text=Usually space is limited .
#Text=It feels a lot like hanging out with a group of friends and just finding what you genuinely like talking about , what you find funny about certain things .
#Text=Like you come up with your own vocabulary for how to discuss ideas .
#Text=It just sort of becomes this little um I guess summer camp type thing where it 's like insular and it 's a , it 's a community .
#Text=And I mean I feel like writers room , and I 've spoken to people about that , all reflect the show runner and what he or she wants out of that .
#Text=Wayne 's journey to running the room for Late Night with Jimmy Fallon was a little less than typical .
#Text=There 's something called a writer 's packet where , as comedian or writer they put down , they do sample monologue jokes , you do sample sketch jokes .
#Text=I never have had a packet .
#Text=What happened was Jimmy Fallon was hired to take over for Conan , who was taking over for Jay Leno .
#Text=That was what was going on .
#Text=Lorne Michaels told Jimmy he 's like , I want you to go out on the road , back on the road and do some standup .
#Text=Now , Jimmy had kind of not been doing that much road was really just an actor .
#Text=So Jimmy contacted me and was like , look , I got to go out on the road .
#Text=I want to get my chops back up .
#Text=Lorne wants me to cuz he sees me in the audience interacting .
#Text=I want to like , do crowd work and stuff .
#Text=Can I open for you on the road ?
#Text=And then during the day we 'll come up with a new act together .
#Text=And we wrote together .
#Text=Like during the day we were just two friends , usually hanging out , trying to make each other laugh .
#Text=I remember there was one bit , I do n't remember the specifics of it , but it was a a GPS joke in the car thing , like the different voices that were talking to you .
#Text=And he would do like the British voice , you know , he could do all of those voices and stuff .
#Text=So we we worked on that .
#Text=And when he first had it , it was just a couple like jokes .
#Text=And by the time I was done with it , there was like 7 or 8 great little punchlines , like , oh , this is great .
#Text=Like he re- I really fleshed it out .
#Text=Wayne 's experience was definitely uncommon .
#Text=Most people do n't just get asked by a show 's star to run their writers ' room .
#Text=In contrast , Anne took a more traditional route to the writers ' room .
#Text=She submitted writing samples .
#Text=And now that she 's actually in the writers ' room , her own real life experience , a background in improv and sketch comedy , has been incredibly useful .
#Text=If you know anything about improv , you 're familiar with the concept of " Yes , And " .

#Text=It 's about creating forward momentum with your collaborator , taking whatever the other performer says and building upon it , always adding information to the original idea in a collaborative spirit .
#Text=The goal is to keep things going and to make something that 's ultimately bigger and better than what you started with .
#Text=But in order to earn the ability to trust and try out new ideas with a group of other people , you 've got to be willing to also maybe look like an idiot from time to time .
#Text=Putting , putting something out there , getting it smashed down in front of everyone , and then immediately , like having to jump back up and like , do it again .

#Text=I think that something that improv and sketch helps with , or at least has helped me with is depersonalizing your connection to whatever is making you laugh at that time because you reali- I 've bombed a thousand times and and it 's sort of my favorite thing is when you 're like , I 'm certain this is hilarious .
#Text=And then and then the audience is like , I 'm certain this is nothing .

#Text=And you just double down for that performance of it because it 's hilarious that your mind thought something was , you know , you have to like be sort of reflective in moments like that of like , okay , yeah , alright , that 's fine .
#Text=And just drop it and continue .

#Text=But also , if you take every , um , every flop joke seriously , you 're going to have a bad day , you know , and it 's more just like a focus on the discussion at the time and what can help move an idea forward or move a certain train of thought forward rather than how can I say the funniest thing right now .
#Text=It 's more like , what is it that we 're really discussing at the heart of it and how do we make that come to the forefront even more than it is now .
